          "page_1": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "When professor V. Faye McNeill gained tenure in 2014, she was the first woman in the chemical engineering department to do so."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“As I was coming up through the tenure track, there was always either one or zero other women in my department,” she said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Over seven years after McNeill received tenure, women make up just 16.9 percent of tenured engineering professors, and Black, Latinx, Native American, or Pacific Islander scholars make up 4.5 percent. Many professors feel that the lack of diversity within tenured faculty means that the system negatively impacts the work environment in their respective departments and weakens Columbia as an academic institution."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Across the University, women make up 29.6 percent of tenured professors, and underrepresented minorities make up just 7.5 percent. By contrast, women make up 54 percent of professors  ineligible for tenure, while “underrepresented minorities” make up 11.6 percent. This follows a broader trend of diverse faculty representation remaining contained to<a href=\"https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2016/08/22/study-finds-gains-faculty-diversity-not-tenure-track\"> the adjunct level</a>."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "TENURE BY GENDER GRAPHIC"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "GenderNewData.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "O’Flaherty said that a fear of not gaining tenure might drive professors to leave the University."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“People don’t go up for tenure unless it’s pretty clear that they’ll get it,” he said. “People will look elsewhere when they think they’re not going to continue.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Mincy noted that the process can be particularly difficult for scholars of color who may come out of graduate school without strong mentorship and guidance on how to be competitive candidates for tenure."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“There isn’t necessarily a sense of direction about where they should go and how they should go,” he said. “Most underrepresented scholars … do not know what the rules are.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Professors seeking tenure at Columbia first go up for one, three, five, and seven-year reviews by their departments. In the arts and sciences, candidates are then reviewed by the Promotion and Tenure Committee, followed by the Tenure Review Advisory Committee.<b> </b>Finally, tenure candidates must be approved by the Board of Trustees. Throughout the process, the candidates are reviewed based on three criteria: research, teaching, and service."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Sociology professor Gil Eyal, a member of TRAC, noted that diversity is not a direct consideration in the tenure process."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“That is not the main way in which the University seeks to diversify its faculty,” he said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Eyal said that the strict standards for receiving tenure at Columbia might complicate bringing diverse faculty to the tenure track."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The tenure process at Columbia is more stringent and harder than at a lot of other schools,” he said. “[This] creates an obstacle when trying to attract top candidates, top minority candidates. ... You have goals of excellence and you have goals of diversification. It’s not the case that you’re completely precluding the other goal, … but there is a balance here."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The University maintains that “[u]nderrepresented faculty at Columbia are no less likely to obtain tenure than their colleagues.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Columbia is dedicated to supporting all faculty, particular historically underrepresented faculty, through faculty orientation, robust professional development offerings, junior and mid career faculty grants, and consistent efforts to enhance the climate of inclusiveness across the University,” Dennis Mitchell, senior vice provost for faculty advancement, wrote in a statement to Spectator."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In an anonymous survey conducted by the Policy Planning Committee in 2018, professors from underrepresented minorities reported feeling that the difficulty of gaining tenure at Columbia required them to make “extra water-tight cases.” The report also displayed disparities in the proportion of underrepresented faculty who are denied or not put up for tenure. 62 percent of underrepresented faculty did not receive tenure or were not put up for tenure, compared to 50 percent of white candidates and 47 percent of Asian candidates. The report found that this disparity was particularly pronounced among Black and Hispanic faculty members."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "FACULTY TENURE BY RACE AND CITIZENSHIP GRAPHIC"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "MinUndergradFaculty.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Piccato, who serves on the Policy Planning Committee, affirmed that professors of color reported feeling more responsibility to “get tenure, … do all of the things that you have to do to get tenure, but also to serve as mentors, advisors, and role models for the students.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Piccato noted that ending this disparity ought to remain an administrative priority."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Obviously, it’s not a process that you can change easily, because it’s established,” he said. “But at least to be mindful that there could be some challenges that need to be addressed, that’s an important consideration.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Helping junior faculty understand how to make a successful case for tenure could help diversify the body of tenured faculty, Mincy said. He said the School of Social Work has made its requirements for tenure clearer since he entered the school in 2001, which has aided the process in becoming more equitable and accessible. Now, he said, we must continue asking, “How do underrepresented scholars become aware of the rules of the game?”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Read on to find out more about how women professors and professors of color build their legacies at the University. </i>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Staff writer Talia Traskos-Hart can be contacted at </i><i>talia.traskos-hart@columbiaspectator.com</i><i>. Follow her on Twitter at</i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/ColumbiaSpec?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor\"><i> </i></a><a href=\"https://twitter.com/ColumbiaSpec?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor\"><i>@taliakth</i></a><i>.</i>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<i>Deputy Editor Stella Pagkas can be contacted at </i><i>stella.pagkas@columbiaspectator.com</i><i>. Follow her on Twitter</i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/stellapagkas\"><i> </i></a><a href=\"https://twitter.com/stellapagkas\"><i>@stellapagkas</i></a><i>.</i>"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "<b>Want to keep up with breaking news? Subscribe to our</b><a href=\"https://columbiaspectator.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe?u=a3d2eeb1ae5560ca04f82f042&id=e51c51d62d\"><b> </b></a><a href=\"https://columbiaspectator.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe?u=a3d2eeb1ae5560ca04f82f042&id=e51c51d62d\"><b>email newsletter</b></a><b> </b><b>and like Spectator on</b><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/columbiaspectator\"><b> </b></a><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/columbiaspectator\"><b>Facebook</b></a><b>.</b>"
            }
          ],
          "page_2": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "After they have secured tenure, many faculty members begin to consider their lasting institutional impact. But for the vast majority of women and underrepresented minorities, this later stage of a career in academia is uncharted territory."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“While you’re getting tenure, the whole name of the game is to impress other people. And that means after 10 years you have proven yourself, and now you don’t have to do that anymore,” Chilton said. “You are allowed to go in any direction you want.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to mathematics professor Michael Thaddeus, there are two ways in which a professor might create a legacy at the University. The first is by contributing to a groundbreaking academic discovery which makes a real impact in its area of study. The second is the creation of an institutional structure that will last after the professor is no longer there: designing a course or major, or establishing a committee."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "These aspirations, which are daunting for any professor, may be particularly intimidating for someone with little representation in their field who cannot identify with those who have shaped the discipline in the past. Chilton recalled entering her career with very few female “academic heroes”; Piccato said he was the first Latin American professor in his department; and Siddiqui found herself teaching discoveries made primarily by “rich white men.” In addition to their academic work, each professor found themselves having to help establish a new precedent in their respective fields."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Piccato explained that, while strides in faculty diversity are beneficial for academia, the burden of inclusion can fall on those from underrepresented groups."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“My experience is that, [after tenure], I was called to do a lot of service for the University. …  I was asked to do things for the department for arts and sciences, serving in committees, institutes and centers,” he said. “And I felt that I had to say yes to a lot of those things, because I thought that having my point of view contribute to the perspective of a committee was going to be useful.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Chilton felt a similar pressure to participate in conversations surrounding inclusivity, particularly because she worried that committees concerned with issues like sexual harassment could easily be used to cover up problems, rather than address them."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I’ve seen the diversity problems. And so when there’s a panel on that, I’m like, ‘Please don’t do that without me because I know what this is like,’” she said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "This commitment to participating in the discourse surrounding diversity presents additional work that many underrepresented faculty members may feel that they have to take on in addition to their jobs as professors and researchers. Although these conversations are undeniably important, investing part of their time in this additional work can set a faculty member from a diverse background behind, while their white, male counterparts devote themselves entirely to the teaching and discoveries that go on to win awards."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Efforts to include underrepresented faculty members in these conversations can also become tokenizing, particularly for professors of color, who may be expected to participate in diversity initiatives solely because of their racial identities. Siddiqui recalls a forum that the University hosted during the Black Lives Matter protests of summer 2020."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“They really did pull their faculty who were more diverse, and I was asked to be on it,” she said. “We were setting up this committee. We all talked about it and said, ‘So we're the ones who have to do the extra work now.’”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Creating such a formal environment to discuss diversity is a step toward a more inclusive academy. However, such committees may have a counterproductive effect on what Thaddeus described as a “healthy atmosphere,” in which underrepresented faculty feel that they can comfortably be a part of the institution. For Siddiqui, this manifested in the feeling that diversity and identity could only be discussed in these formal spaces, and that it was still unacceptable to discuss them casually. To achieve real inclusivity, she said, this discourse should be more ingrained in day-to-day academic work."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "A lack of transparency also presents a barrier to any faculty member looking to make an impact in their department but particularly to those from underrepresented backgrounds and identities. In many departments, this may look like undisclosed reasoning for hiring or promotion, or unspoken traditions or norms."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“There are a lot of unwritten rules about how things should be done, and you really need somebody to share them with you,” Piccato said. “In the past, they were shared in small groups of people who look the same.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Siddiqui, this gatekeeping, along with the general uncertainty associated with a long-term career in academia, has pushed many individuals from historically marginalized groups to pursue other careers. There is no clear road map for a long and impactful career in academia, and many feel unequipped to pave that road themselves."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Chilton also added that income is not always guaranteed in academia—another barrier that may prevent someone in a marginalized group seeking social or economic mobility from making their mark in their chosen field. This issue is exacerbated by the markedly lower salaries that academics from marginalized backgrounds and identities reportedly receive."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Based on the sample of professors who completed the PPC’s anonymous survey, salaries for male professors were significantly higher than those for female professors."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The report found that “two men made one and a half standard deviations above the mean of their department whereas the highest-paid woman made only one standard deviation above the mean.” One professor called pay disparities one of “the most discouraging aspects of being at Columbia.” In tandem, 67 percent of men reported having the resources to successfully do their jobs, compared to 53 percent of women."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In the report, another professor anonymously said that her “Columbia salary was inadequate to pay for her expenses including childcare.” While inequalities in pay are difficult to measure on a large scale due to the confidential nature of professors’ salaries, this suspected wage gap is yet another discouraging factor for women and underrepresented minorities looking to establish a lasting career in academia."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "For many individuals trying to make an impact on academia in spite of a lack of representation, mentorship is both the solution to the problem and a facet of that future legacy."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Chilton, whose mentors and role models in computer science were often men, strives to make her courses accessible to women looking to make a place for themselves in that field."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I feel like I make a difference,” she said. “A lot of my stuff uses language and visual arts and computing. A lot of women just tend to gravitate to language arts very often, and so being able to include that in STEM is powerful. So I feel like I'm part of the solution.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Siddiqui said her experience at the University has been unique because she found a mentor with whom she could identify—another woman of color in chemistry."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Being recognized in that way from someone who … identifies very much like you do, and seeing that they’ve gone through a struggle and succeeded just gives you that hope that it’s gonna get better and you can get there too and gives you that drive to keep on going,” she said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "This support has helped Siddiqui overcome some of the barriers that she has faced as a woman of color in science, and she hopes to provide that same mentorship to the next generation of academics. It is her hope that young, underrepresented students coming into the field will find it easier to make that lasting impact and this, in turn, can be a part of Siddiqui’s own legacy."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“When students come back to me and say that I’ve inspired them to go into chemistry that just makes me feel so incredibly happy,” she said. “Especially when it’s women who come up and say they want to go into hard sciences, and I’m just like, ‘Yeah, you deserve to be there. You’re just as smart as everybody else. You deserve to be there.’”"
            },
